h3. Problem Definition
On the page *Issues > Search for issues*, the JQL query is updated with an statement {{ORDER BY <FIELD>}} when clicking on a column header to sort the results by that field. For example, considering the current search is as follows:
{code:none|borderStyle=solid|borderColor=#6A8EB3|bgColor=#F8F8F8}
project = "Jira Server and Data Center" 
{code}

After clicking in the column header for field *Created*, which is a system field, the query is updated to:
{code:none|borderStyle=solid|borderColor=#6A8EB3|bgColor=#F8F8F8}
project = "Jira Server and Data Center" ORDER BY created ASC
{code}

However, if the field in question is a custom field, the JQL will be updated with the custom field ID instead of its name. For example, when clicking on a column for a custom field called *Symptom Severity*, the JQL will be updated as follows:
{code:none|borderStyle=solid|borderColor=#6A8EB3|bgColor=#F8F8F8}
project = "Jira Server and Data Center" ORDER BY cf[17130] ASC
{code}

h3. Suggested Solution
Change the behavior to reference the custom field by its name instead of its ID. In the case above, it would be expected that the JQL query would be updated as follows:
{code:none|borderStyle=solid|borderColor=#6A8EB3|bgColor=#F8F8F8}
project = "Jira Server and Data Center" ORDER BY "Symptom Severity" ASC
{code}

Note that the JQL query above is valid and works correctly, meaning it is currently possible to reference a custom field by its name, but Jira will reference it by its ID when sorting by clicking on the column header.

h3. Workaround
None.

The customer has requested: C style comments (what they call as block comments) are in the SQL standard since 2003 should be rendered by WikiRenderer in the same way, but it is seen as a reserved word

Reproduce: open a comment, in Text mode, and type

~~
{code:sql}

-- This is a line comment
/* this is a block comment */

{code}
~~
Note the line comment is shown "greyed-out", the block comment has "is" highlighted as a reserved word expected now.

h3. Issue Summary

Not selecting any sub-task while performing Bulk operation loses the current search
h3. Environment

Tested on Jira Software
 * 7.13.5
 * 7.13.6
 * 8.4

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # {color:#000000}Login to Jira Instance{color}
 # {color:#000000}Browse to you issue having sub-tasks you want to perform the Bulk Operation ON.{color}
 # {color:#000000}Move to the Sub-Tasks section click ... over there{color}
 # {color:#000000}Click on Bulk operations{color}
 # {color:#000000}Now you would have the screen showing only Sub-Tasks{color}
 # {color:#000000}Just click on Next w/o choosing any Sub-Task{color}
 # {color:#000000}You would see now the listed issue have all other issues listed, due to losing its current search filter {color}

h3.  Expected Results

It should still show the earlier search results.
h3. Actual Results

From actions.xml

[https://stash.atlassian.com/projects/JIRASERVER/repos/jira/browse/jira-components/jira-core/src/main/resources/actions.xml?at=refs%2Ftags%2F7.13.6] 
{noformat}
<action name="issue.bulkedit.BulkEdit1" alias="BulkEdit1">
        <view name="input">/secure/views/bulkedit/bulkedit.jsp</view>
        <view name="error">/secure/views/bulkedit/bulkedit.jsp</view>
</action>
{noformat}
 
h3. Workaround

Not from the Product end, but the user can go back via the browser.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-12724].
  {panel}

There should be a new global permission "create projects".
Project Adminstrators cannot create projects. But they administer some projects of a certain domain and want to create a new project in this domain.

h3. Summary

